The bone house is still fascinating after 100 years. Take a look into the interiors of Gaudi.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase at a spinal column of dinosaur and the balconies at open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona of architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the premises the nickname of House in bone.
Organic shapes, wild colours, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade resembling scalps and curves everywhere, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau d'Antoni Gaudi.
The frontal façade of the house runs its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that resemble nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation you can see geometry, pace and order thought with precision.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colours is reinforced.
The rolling and torsion of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood reproduces in wave the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the onion and the lamells.
The house Battlo, which sits in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia number. 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another whole new one, but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and better market reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multiple housing house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for a representation apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the façade.
For the façade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of the house Casa Battlo began with a successive cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park where there are other works of Gaudi.
The premises named the hot house just after its finish because of its organic forms "the House in bone".
Others, in view of the specific window opening mechanism, called it "the house that slaps".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint Georges the boss of Catalonia.
Other construction sculpture elements contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with air vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation of Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction guidelines of then and did not allow itself to be hampered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained the permit from the city to build, knowing, of course, that the data on reconstruction plans were so vague that two years after the completion the municipal council was horrified and requested changes.
For example, municipal council members did not like the building pillars emptied on the public trottoir.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call from the city Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third one a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase by which you can access an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit itself to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has also received new façades with a non-traditional towel and two floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard and with the wells of lights are decorated.
The game with two colours gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than darkness that, on the contrary, absorbs the sun rays.
The House Casa Battlo, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a profitable company and extended the field of visits to common spaces and towers including rooftop terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist cards holders have 20% discounts.
The sum is still above the entry price in the other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
