Apparatus to follow people are increasingly requested by parents who want to watch their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think of monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, established at the beginning to search for cars can as well be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases as exemplary as that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of lights but will soon be of a watch size.
The case of little Anicka touched a large number of people and they started looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin from MAcro Weil, which is one of the suppliers of tracing equipment on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as put it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet met such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who really buy the product for safety reasons," Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know what the "box" is used for and how to use it in emergency situations.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear one of these things on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something intentionally when they don't want to be under control.'
"Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
In her view, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly controversial.
"If this is a prepared raft, the author will do everything he can to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
"currently, it's the phone."
"When tracking devices are going to develop, they (the criminals) will look for them too because the sale will be supported by a advertising campaign."
"In such cases, criminals will always be in advance on the police," said the psychologist.
It admits that such devices can help in an unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the RC Monitoring company, which provides tracking services for both cars and people, claims that having such a device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an aggression.
"The device may be set in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
"The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and is in a position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special software.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to the device that is attached to the size of a lighting box or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can still lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the possible aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Well, he will realize that after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracing device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of systems for acquiring a position using the GPS (which is commonly used in autonavigating) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
