Longer than yearly index is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the longer index than the year are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of male hormone testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before 60 years of age," announced the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, Professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be subjected to prostate cancer testing, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, added Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Great Britain followed over 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the year.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
However, in the case of those who had the longer index than the year, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years of age, the risk reduction reached 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, inter alia, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Prof. Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech genetician and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he was aware of this study, but that he did not seem, he did not think, that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer was "completely demonstrated".
