These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it follows changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerged from this year's survey results in September and early October.
The first is the pretty sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from at least 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
