A microbe tolerating arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say that this shows that life has opportunities beyond major elements that have been considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That is why it is very special, even though it is far from being a truly "extraordinary form of life," commented Paul Davies C. W. of the State University of Arizona, co-author of the report contained in the online edition of the journal Science on Thursday.
Six major elements were long considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after having replaced phosphorus with arsenic.
"We are wondering what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. from the State University of Arizona, co-author of the report.
Discovery is important in life research beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, generated widespread speculations on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of alien life.
This was not the case.
The discovery "hows that, in other global environments, organizations could be able to use other elements to act on biochemistry and that the "standard" set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be established," commented Charles Cockell, Professor at the Institute of Global and Spacial Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in basic biochemistry and the biochemical structure," added Cockell.
It wasn't a stubborn discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from the NASA Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; so it speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behaviour is really similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, the organizations have difficulty separating these elements."
"But the arsenic is sufficiently different so that it does not work exactly like phosphorus; it enters inside and, in some way, gums the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
Researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing arsenic concentrations to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, Deputy Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
Arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the Earth's existence, she said; so the researchers made the assumption that the first forms of life could have been used.
This suggests that there might be other ways of forming life, not only the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
Research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
