The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders did not give rise to any breakthroughs on the major issues to be dealt with during the session of the "Black Candle".
But clearly, there was at least a polite discussion on the differences between the two sides and on the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to mark points.
The Wednesday public meeting of the Committee on the President's Deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap, but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual trial in order to achieve signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed party war.
That is why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments from the participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether tax, expenditure, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
Nevertheless, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"It is no doubt that things have changed on the tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration officer, now next to the Ethics and Public Policy Centre.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
Elections raise partisan passions, and then they swell.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the session of the "lazy duck", the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve a part or the whole of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment allowances, because the Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, while refusing unemployment allowances for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, more optimism is based on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session relating to the "lumpy duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston, from the Brookings Institution, warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily mean a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he said, a period of disagreement is likely or even inevitable.
"When things that must be done will be done, in the short term psychology will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed its broadly shared skepticism that civilization would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what is happening between today and 2012 as a pre-spectacle or shadow-boxing compared to the 2012 main event, he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the electors present in the Tea that contributed to its creation.
