These partisan positions are already clear in the first response to the Deficit Commission's recommendations that include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, deferring retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their opinion, imposed the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, consisting of 18 members, to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they had difficulty reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group, suggesting that there are little motives or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston plans two phases in the battles between the White House and the Congress republikans.
The first will be in the form of partisan confrontations next year, since the Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartite cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the supportive spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans always want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged as losing will have to change his mind and find compromises.
However, this would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are larger today than they were in the middle of the 1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological difference between Obama and the republicans of Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and the republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties saw 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
In view of this reality, the civility presented this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But there will be much more effort on both sides to find a ground of agreement on issues that still divide them.
