The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
Persons must go to Visa Applicants Service Centres before interviewing in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure for the processing of visas at the Embassy and United States consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to present themselves at the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC, according to its seals in English) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will provide some benefits for the applicants, including the following:
The total cost to treat the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another to allow the mail service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment covering the three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to present themselves in an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearer CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
