A Global Plan for Renewing Lighting
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction required to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is the result of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún in order to compensate for the lack of binding commitments for reduction by industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the fluorescent lamps that still monopolize from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact lamps or, better, by electroluminescent diodes lamps (DEL or "LED" in English), the majority of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG released on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the global car park emissions.
Last year, in Copenhagen, large issuer countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, further 5 Gts will need to be removed from this balance sheet to stabilize the climate up to 2 centigrades by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy dissolves in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy spending is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by two times more.
The fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED lamps, such as those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - this company has also participated in the United Nations study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a glowing lamp, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to producing very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown reserves for fluocompact bulbs as they contain mercury and that they must be removed as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal thermal plants, which emits a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants are producing 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits of each country through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars per year for electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
