Unemployment remained stable in France in the 3rd quarter
The unemployment rate in France, within the meaning of the International Labour Office (BIT), remained stable at 9.3% in the metropolitan area (9.7% in the overseas departments), showing the seasonally adjusted data (CVS) published by the Insee on Thursday.
The number of unemployed is 2.631 million in metropolitan areas.
Data from the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3% of the metropolitan active population and 9.7% with the DOMs.
Over a year, unemployment has risen by 0.1 points.
More generally, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether they were available or not within two weeks for work and whether they were looking for employment.
The situation of young people in the labour market has continued to deteriorate, with a further rise in unemployment, rising to 24.2% in metropolitan areas (+ 0.9 points over three months, + 0.5 points over one year) and 25% including the DOMs.
In the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15-24 were unemployed within the meaning of ILO.
Seniors experienced a slight increase in unemployment, at 6.4% in metropolitan areas (+0.2 points over three months and over one year), or 482,000 people over the age of 50, and 6.6% with the DOMs.
Only 25-49 years of age benefited from stable unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in metropolitan areas (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
The Insee has not published any monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a polemic on its calculation method.
Eurostat, the European Union Statistics Agency, on the other hand, continues to do so and announced a rate of 9.8% for France (including DOM) in October after 9.9% in September.
