The EU announced that it had reached €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to meet its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, be "new and additional" in order to ensure that additional efforts are made without being at the expense of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what means "new and additional".
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States of which France have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start-up funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of public development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditures in previous years or at the overall level of public development assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Again there is no rule and everyone chooses how to calculate it.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 loan is equal to €1 given.
Of course, this is hardly justified: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emissions mitigation projects that are based on more efficient technologies), it is necessary to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent to a euro that is given... At the most, only the cost of the loan for the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be accounted for under its commitments.
However, France has only made such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making EUR 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to check by yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other cases) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union pays €1 to meet its commitment, France only spends 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice passport tour!
In summary, in its fast start-up financing, France is doing a double fraud: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action in time and, on the other, on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it can believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has achieved arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to borrow?) and in the negotiations as the developing countries are not completely dubbed...
The chapter on early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
